<div id="review_937416000" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/937416000" />
    <a title="Lin Roberts" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18918447-lin-roberts"><img alt="Lin Roberts" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1400114431p2/18918447.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/937416000?book_show_action=true">May 14, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lin Roberts" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lin Roberts" href="/user/show/18918447-lin-roberts">Lin Roberts</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer937416000&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer937416000" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9289836281482413037">I was hoping to like Natchez Burning after deciding to devote time reading through Greg Iles almost 800 page thriller, but I&apos;ve got some serious issues with this story:<br/>1. Too many loose ends for a novel this size- What happens to Viola&apos;s son? Was it purely a Mercy killing? Why was the &quot;good&quot; Doctor cavorting with the Klansmen, as portrayed in the incriminating photo and at the time of the murder?<br/>2. All the positive Black characters get killed off, one notably in effort to save Penn Cage and his </span>
  <span id="freeText9289836281482413037" style="display:none">I was hoping to like Natchez Burning after deciding to devote time reading through Greg Iles almost 800 page thriller, but I've got some serious issues with this story:<br />1. Too many loose ends for a novel this size- What happens to Viola's son? Was it purely a Mercy killing? Why was the "good" Doctor cavorting with the Klansmen, as portrayed in the incriminating photo and at the time of the murder?<br />2. All the positive Black characters get killed off, one notably in effort to save Penn Cage and his fiancé. Sleepy Johnstone returns to Mississippi to avenge his friends murder by a Klansmen after having migrated north to Detroit 30-40 years earlier ?Really.<br />3. The 2 Black women( Viola, Swan) who had encounters with the 2 "liberal" white guys in the story ( Tom, Henry) are portrayed as the sexual initiators if not aggressors in the relationships.<br />Think I'll skip the next 2 installments of this trilogy.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9289836281482413037" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

